-- Sensitive Index Surges on Foreign Inflows; Maruti, Wipro Shares Advance
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2010-10-13T10:07:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-13/sensitive-index-rises-on-foreign-inflows-jsw-steel-hindalco-shares-gain.html
India’s stocks rose as foreign
investors bought more shares than they sold for the 29th
straight day after reports from China, Japan and Australia
signaled that the global economic recovery is strengthening.  Maruti Suzuki India Ltd. , the nation’s biggest carmaker,
climbed to its highest level since December. Overseas  funds 
bought a net  11.1 billion rupees  ($250.8 million) of Indian
equities on Oct. 11, extending this year’s record inflows to
998.7 billion rupees, according to the nation’s market
regulator.  Wipro Ltd. , the third-biggest software services
provider, surged the most in five months.  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 469.24, or 2.3 percent, to 20,672.58, according to
preliminary closing prices. The gauge has gained 29 percent from
the May 25 low, approaching the record closing high of 20,873.33
on Jan. 8, 2008, and is the best performer this year among the
world’s 10 biggest stock markets.  The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange rose
2.3 percent to 6,231.50. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 1.9 percent
to 2,623.03.  To contact the reporter on this story:
